searchNodes=[{"doc":"Controller for fetching location for given IP address","ref":"IPLocator.Controllers.LocationController.html","title":"IPLocator.Controllers.LocationController","type":"module"},{"doc":"","ref":"IPLocator.Controllers.LocationController.html#get_location/1","title":"IPLocator.Controllers.LocationController.get_location/1","type":"function"},{"doc":"Plug based HTTP request router","ref":"IPLocator.Router.html","title":"IPLocator.Router","type":"module"},{"doc":"Callback implementation for Plug.call/2 .","ref":"IPLocator.Router.html#call/2","title":"IPLocator.Router.call/2","type":"function"},{"doc":"Callback implementation for Plug.init/1 .","ref":"IPLocator.Router.html#init/1","title":"IPLocator.Router.init/1","type":"function"},{"doc":"Simple Plug based HTTP server for querying IP location This is a HTTP wrapper for Geo library. Sample server is deployed at ip-locator.fly.dev , check it out! curl -sLi ip-locator.fly.dev/location/180.219.213.135 This server is loaded with provided sample dummy data. Documentation: https://akash-akya.github.io/docs/ip-locator Endpoints Server exposes single endpoint. GET /location/&lt;IP Address&gt; Returns json encoded location data as response. Please check API spec in openapi.yaml for more details Dependencies PostgreSQL Elixir v1.14 Erlang/OTP v25.x Development To get started you can use docker-compose run PostgreSQL which is a dependency for Geo # start database $ docker-compose up # create database $ mix ecto.create -r Geo.Repo # run migrations $ mix ecto.migrate -r Geo.Repo Load sample dummy data $ mix geo.import samples/sample.csv Run the application server $ mix run --no-halt Test the API $ curl -si localhost:4001/location/180.219.213.135 NOTE Not using Phoenix since as the requirement is simple. Production Deployment Building the container Dockerfile is provided to build a the server as container to simplify the packaging and deployment. We use mix release to package the server which is then copied to a container which is easier to deploy Since Geo is in a private git repo we need to pass a whitelisted private key to be able to pull the code. docker build --build-arg IP_LOCATOR_PRIVATE_KEY=&quot;$(cat id_ed25519 | base64)&quot; -t ip_locator . You can now push this container to docker registry of your choice and can run the container. Configuration Set following environment variables DATABASE_URL : (mandatory) database URL string, example: ecto://USER:PASS@HOST/DATABASE PORT : (optional) HTTP server port. Defaults to 4001 Refer Geo docs for running the migrations. Metrics By default server emit multiple Prometheus metrics in production environment. Metrics will be available at port 9091 and path /metrics you can configure your server to collect metrics at this endpoint Importing Location Data There are multiple ways to import data in production connect to production database locally and run the mix task, this is simpler approach with Platforms like Fly.io copy csv file to production server and run the mix task in a production server. If you don't have access to mix task then you can use an approach similar to the one mentioned for database migration above Above approaches works but might be unsafe since we are exposing access to production database and server. Safer approach can be to run scheduled job and import data programattically either using any background job scheduler or using Kubernetes Job if you are already running Kubernetes. If you are deploying this server in Fly.io you can use check fly.toml configuration as reference. This is the config which used for running ip-locator.fly.dev server. Running Tests # start postgres $ docker-compose up $ mix test --trace","ref":"readme.html","title":"IP Locator","type":"extras"}]